# Spaced Repetition and Memory

Spaced repetition is a learning technique that reviews information at ==increasing intervals== to exploit the psychological spacing effect[^ebbinghaus].

## The Forgetting Curve

Without review, memories decay exponentially. Ebbinghaus showed that retention drops to about **21%** after 31 days without reinforcement.

The forgetting curve follows approximately:

$$
R(t) = e^{-t/S}
$$

Where $R$ is retention, $t$ is time, and $S$ is the stability of the memory.

## Optimal Review Schedule

| Review | Interval | Expected Retention |
| :---: | ---: | :---: |
| 1st | 1 day | 90% |
| 2nd | 3 days | 90% |
| 3rd | 7 days | 90% |
| 4th | 14 days | 90% |
| 5th | 30 days | 90% |
| 6th | 90 days | 90% |

## Tools

- [[Anki]] -- the gold standard for spaced repetition
- [[Mochi]] -- modern alternative with Markdown support
- [[RemNote]] -- combines note-taking and SRS

## Card Design Principles

> Make each card test exactly one thing. Avoid "What do you know about X?" cards.

### Good Card Examples

Atomic question
: What is the time complexity of binary search?
: $O(\log n)$

### Bad Card Examples

W> Cards that are too broad lead to inconsistent recall and wasted review time.

## My Workflow

1. Take notes while reading ([[Progressive Summarization]])
2. Extract key concepts into atomic cards
3. Review daily in [[Anki]]
4. Monthly review of card quality

- [x] Set up Anki sync across devices
- [x] Create deck for current book
- [~] Process highlighted passages
- [ ] Review and cull low-quality cards

[^ebbinghaus]: Ebbinghaus, H. (1885). Memory: A Contribution to Experimental Psychology.
